    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Nageia excelsa improperly include experience nausea, trigger seizures, causes diarrhea, cause vomiting, and induces vomiting. This is because Nageia excelsa, a plant native to Southeast Asia, contains toxic compounds such as diterpenes and lignans, which can cause gastrointestinal and neurological symptoms when ingested in large quantities. The improper use of Nageia excelsa can lead to an imbalance of these toxic compounds in the body, resulting in nausea, diarrhea, vomiting, and seizures. These symptoms are due to the disruption of normal physiological processes, including the regulation of electrolyte and water balance in the body. In severe cases, the improper use of Nageia excelsa can lead to life-threatening complications, such as dehydration and respiratory failure.",
    "uses": "Nageia excelsa has been reported to have various medicinal uses in traditional medicine, particularly in Southeast Asia. Its bark and leaves are used to treat fever and other ailments. The plant is also believed to have anti-inflammatory properties, which may help in reducing swelling and pain. In addition, Nageia excelsa is used to treat digestive issues and as an antiseptic agent. Further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal properties and potential uses of this plant.",
    "taxonomy": "Nageia excelsa is classified as a species within the coniferous genus Nageia, which is part of the family Podocarpaceae. This classification makes it a part of the larger plant division Coniferae. Nageia excelsa is native to Southeast Asia and is considered an evergreen tree. The species is also known as the Philippine pine or Damar. It is a slow-growing, long-lived tree that can reach heights of up to 40 meters.",
    "benefits": "Nageia excelsa is known to have various health benefits due to its medicinal properties. The plant is traditionally used in Southeast Asian cultures to treat various ailments, including fever, rheumatism, and respiratory issues. The extract from Nageia excelsa contains flavonoids and other compounds that exhibit antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. These properties are believed to contribute to its potential health benefits, including reducing inflammation and improving immune function. However, more research is needed to fully understand the extent of its health benefits.",
    "parts": "Nageia excelsa, also known as the giant daphne or kauri, is a plant species native to Borneo and Sumatra. While there is limited information available on its traditional medicinal uses, it is known to have been used in various traditional medicine practices in Southeast Asia. However, more research is needed to confirm its effectiveness and potential health benefits. Traditional healers in the region may use the plant's leaves, bark, or roots for medicinal purposes, but specific uses and preparation methods are not well-documented. Further studies are necessary to fully understand the medicinal properties and potential applications of Nageia excelsa.",
    "intro": "Nageia excelsa, also known as Kevazingo, is a species of coniferous tree native to Borneo and the Philippines. It is valued for its medicinal properties, particularly for its potential to reduce inflammation and improve respiratory health, making it a popular remedy for conditions such as bronchitis and asthma. The bioactive constituents of Nageia excelsa include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional herbal medicine, Nageia excelsa is often used to make teas, infusions, and tinctures, which are commonly used to relieve respiratory symptoms and promote overall well-being."
